{"title_page": "Alberto Tejada Noriega", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Tejada|Noriega}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Alberto Tejada Noriega\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|office      = [[Ministry of Health (Peru)|Health Minister of Peru]]\n|president   = [[Ollanta Humala]]\n|term_start  = 28 July 2011\n|term_end    = 23 July 2012\n|succeeding  =\n|predecessor =\n|successor   =\n|birth_date  = {{Birth-date and age|11 November 1956}}\n|birth_place = [[Lima]], Peru\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       =\n|religion    =\n}}\n\n'''Alberto Tejada Noriega''' (born 11 November 1956<ref>http://www.weltfussball.de/schiedsrichter_profil/alberto-tejada/</ref> in [[Lima, Peru]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}) was the [[Peru]]vian Minister of Health between 2011 and 2012. He was also a [[urology|urologist]] and later a [[association football|football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]].<ref name=\"lr\"/>\n\n==Football career==\nHe refereed three matches in the [[FIFA World Cup]], two in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] and one in [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]].<ref>https://int.soccerway.com/referees/alberto-tejada-noriega/106820/</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he ran against Manuel Burga to head the [[Peruvian Football Federation]].<ref name=\"lr\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was the mayor of [[San Borja District]] (2003\u20132006 and 2007-2010).<ref name=\"lr\">>http://www.larepublica.pe/24-07-2011/gabinete-alberto-tejada-iria-al-ministerio-de-salud-y-miguel-caillaux-agricultura {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110802070357/http://www.larepublica.pe/24-07-2011/gabinete-alberto-tejada-iria-al-ministerio-de-salud-y-miguel-caillaux-agricultura |date=2011-08-02 }}</ref> He was the Peruvian Minister of Health during the presidency of [[Ollanta Humala]], between July 28, 2011 and July 23, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.andina.com.pe/Ingles/Noticia.aspx?id=R0FYnCOUizg= |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920061108/http://www.andina.com.pe/ingles/Noticia.aspx?Id=R0FYnCOUizg= |archive-date=2011-09-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was elected mayor of San Borja for a their term (2019-2022) with [[Popular Action (Peru)]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Soccerway referee|alberto-tejada-noriega/106820}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{WorldReferee.com}}\n\n{{Humala-Lerner government}}\n{{Humala-Valdes government}}\n{{1998 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tejada Noriega, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Peruvian football referees]]\n[[Category:Peruvian urologists]]\n[[Category:Peruvian people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lima]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica referees]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Peru]]\n\n\n{{Peru-footy-bio-stub}}\n{{Peru-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|Tejada|Noriega}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name        = Alberto Tejada Noriega\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|office      = [[Ministry of Health (Peru)|Health Minister of Peru]]\n|president   = [[Ollanta Humala]]\n|term_start  = 28 July 2011\n|term_end    = 23 July 2012\n|succeeding  =\n|predecessor =\n|successor   =\n|birth_date  = 11 November 1956\n|birth_place =\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       =\n|religion    =\n}}\n'''Alberto Tejada Noriega''' (born 11 November 1956<ref>http://www.weltfussball.de/schiedsrichter_profil/alberto-tejada/</ref> in [[Lima, Peru]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}) was the [[Peru]]vian Minister of Health between 2011 and 2012. He was also a [[urology|urologist]] and later a [[association football|football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]].<ref name=\"lr\"/>\n\n==Football career==\nHe refereed three matches in the [[FIFA World Cup]], two in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] and one in [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]].<ref>https://int.soccerway.com/referees/alberto-tejada-noriega/106820/</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he ran against Manuel Burga to head the [[Peruvian Football Federation]].<ref name=\"lr\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was the mayor of [[San Borja District]] (2003\u20132006 and 2007-2010).<ref name=\"lr\">>http://www.larepublica.pe/24-07-2011/gabinete-alberto-tejada-iria-al-ministerio-de-salud-y-miguel-caillaux-agricultura {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110802070357/http://www.larepublica.pe/24-07-2011/gabinete-alberto-tejada-iria-al-ministerio-de-salud-y-miguel-caillaux-agricultura |date=2011-08-02 }}</ref> He was the Peruvian Minister of Health during the presidency of [[Ollanta Humala]], between July 28th, 2011 and July 23rd, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.andina.com.pe/Ingles/Noticia.aspx?id=R0FYnCOUizg= |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920061108/http://www.andina.com.pe/ingles/Noticia.aspx?Id=R0FYnCOUizg= |archive-date=2011-09-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was elected mayor of San Borja for a their term (2019-2022) with [[Popular Action (Peru)]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Humala-Lerner government}}\n{{Humala-Valdes government}}\n{{1998 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tejada Noriega, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Peruvian football referees]]\n[[Category:Peruvian urologists]]\n[[Category:Peruvian people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lima]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica referees]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Peru]]\n\n\n{{Peru-footy-bio-stub}}\n{{Peru-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alberto_Tejada_Noriega"}
{"title_page": "\u00c9ric Dumont-Baltet", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=November 2013}}\n'''\u00c9ric Dumont''' is a [[France|French]] [[horticulturalist]] and [[nursery (horticulture)|nursery]] [[gardener]] in [[Troyes]] in the [[d\u00e9partement in France|French d\u00e9partement]] [[Aube]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valeursactuelles.com/culture/actualit%C3%A9/eric-dumont-lart-verger20120726.html|title=Eric Dumont, l'art du verger|work=Valeurs Actuelles|author=Bruno Cessole|date=26 July 2012|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> He is the son of the pilot [[Charles Dumont (pilot)|Charles Dumont]] and great-grandson of the famous horticulturist [[Charles Baltet]].\n\nHe is considered an [[orchard]] specialist as he has conserved various old fruit-bearing varieties and the centuries-old knowledge of caring for them. He presents numerous gardening and orchard [[television program]]mes with the French actor, author and presenter [[Jean-Pierre Coffe]]. In 2000 he published a book entitled ''Les Vergers \u00e0 l'ancienne'' (''The Orchards of Old'').\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumont-Baltet, Eric}}\n[[Category:French gardeners]]\n[[Category:French horticulturists]]\n[[Category:French garden writers]]\n[[Category:French television presenters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=November 2013}}\n'''\u00c9ric Dumont''' is a [[France|French]] [[horticulturalist]] and [[nursery (horticulture)|nursery]] [[gardener]] in [[Troyes]] in the [[d\u00e9partement in France|French d\u00e9partement]] [[Aube]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valeursactuelles.com/culture/actualit%C3%A9/eric-dumont-lart-verger20120726.html|title=Eric Dumont, l'art du verger|work=Valeurs Actuelles|author=Bruno Cessole|date=26 July 2012|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> He is the son of the pilot [[Charles Dumont (pilot)|Charles Dumont]] and great-grandson of the famous horticulturist [[Charles Baltet]].\n\nHe is considered an [[orchard]] specialist as he has conserved various old fruit-bearing varieties and the centuries-old knowledge of caring for them. He presents numerous gardening and orchard [[television program]]mes with the French actor, author and presenter [[Jean-Pierre Coffe]]. In 2000 he published a book entitled ''Les Vergers \u00e0 l'ancienne'' (''The Orchards of Old'').\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumont-Baltet, Eric}}\n[[Category:French gardeners]]\n[[Category:French horticulturists]]\n[[Category:French garden writers]]\n[[Category:French television presenters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89ric_Dumont-Baltet"}
{"title_page": "Zal and Rudabeh", "text_new": "{{Infobox\n | bodystyle    = \n | bodyclass    = vcard\n | titlestyle   = \n | title        = \n | abovestyle   = background: #CD853F\n | aboveclass   = fn org\n | above        = Zal and Rudabeh\n | imagestyle   =\n | captionstyle = \n | image        = [[File:Rudaba.JPG|center|260px]]\n | caption       =[[Z\u0101l]] and [[Rudaba]] love each other\n\n | headerstyle  = background: #F0E68C\n | labelstyle   = \n | datastyle    =\n\n | header1      =[[Shahnameh]] Stories\n | label2       =\n | data2        =\n | label3       =\n | data3        =\n | label4       =\n | data4        =\n | label5       =\n | data5        =\n | label6       =\n | data6        =\n | label7       =\n | data7        =\n | header14     =\n | label15      =\n | data15       =\n | label16      =\n | data16       =\n | label17      =\n | data17       =\n | label18      =\n | data18       =\n | label19      =\n | data19       =\n | label20      =\n | data20       =\n | header21     =\n | label22      =\n | data22       =\n | label23      =\n | data23       =\n | label24      =\n | data24       =\n | label25      =\n | data25       =\n}}\n\n\n\n'''Zal and Rudaba''' ({{lang-fa|\u0632\u0627\u0644 \u0648 \u0631\u0648\u062f\u0627\u0628\u0647}}) are the fate of two lovers in Shahnameh. [[Z\u0101l]]'s love for [[Rudaba]] begins when he enters the suburbs of Kabol under the rule of the governor and hears [[Mehrab Kaboli|Mehrab]], the ruler of [[Kabul (Shahnameh)|Kabol]], have a daughter in the palace. Zal was ruling as a teenager in Zabol and was ordered by King [[Manuchehr]] of Iran. It was likely that the tax collection of the countries under the command of Iran was with Zal, and he camped with his battalion on the outskirts of Kabol.<ref>Zal traveled to Hinduwan and entered the cities of [[Kabul (Shahnameh)|Kabol]], [[Dunbar (Shahnameh)|Dunbar]], [[Murg (Shahnameh)|Morg]] and [[Mai (Shahnameh)|Mai]].</ref>\n\n==Dating Zal and Mehrab==\nMehrab was the ruler of Kabul and the father of Rudaba. Mehrab paid his taxes to [[S\u0101m]] as usual, but now his successor is Zal. Mehrab found that Zal had camped on the outskirts of the city, visiting in the morning but with an annual ransom. When Zal was aware of Mehrab's arrival, he accepted her and welcomed her into the Zuboliani tradition and placed her in a high position in parliament. When the party ended and a farewell to Mehrab, one of Zal's commanders told him that Mehrab had a beautiful daughter in the palace. And Zal fell in love with Mehrab's daughter.\n\nZal was upset at night, but the next day Mehrab went to Zal's tent again for lunch. Zal was very happy about the arrival of Mehrab. He asked Mehrab what he wanted to express, the throne, the royal seal, the sword or the crown. These compliments indicated a lover. And while he had not yet seen the [[Rudaba]]. In response, Mehrab said, \"I only have one wish to be my guest. Despite the esoteric desire, Zal said Sam would not allow me to do so, and Mehrab left hi tent discomfort.\n\n==Zal and white hair==\nMehrab returned to the palace and praised Zal's glamorous qualities for his wife [[Sindukht]], but said the gladiator had only one flaw and that he had white hair. [[Rudaba]] heard the talk but fell in love with Zal' character and wished he could understand her better. Rudaba was restless like Zal and sent five of her slaves to the Zal tent to get to know each other. Eventually, one night Zal climbed the wall of the palace with Rudaba's escort, and the two lovers' wishes came true. But an acute problem later emerged, and it was the [[Iran (Shahnameh)|Iran]] king's opposition to their marriage.<ref>[[Manuchehr]] believed that their marriage would be a two-pronged generation that would be dangerous for Iran. And [[Rostam]] was the result of their marriage. </ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[Ferdowsi]] Shahnameh. From the Moscow version. Mohammed Publishing. {{ISBN | 964-5566-35-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Shahnameh}}\n{{Other Shahnameh characters}}\n\n[[Category:Shahnameh characters]]\n[[Category:Women in Shahnameh]]\n[[Category:Shahnameh stories]]\n[[Category:Shahnameh stubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox\n | bodystyle    = \n | bodyclass    = vcard\n | titlestyle   = \n | title        = \n | abovestyle   = background: #CD853F\n | aboveclass   = fn org\n | above        = Zal and Rudabeh\n | imagestyle   =\n | captionstyle = \n | image        = [[File:Rudaba.JPG|center|260px]]\n | caption       =[[Z\u0101l]] and [[Rudaba]] love each other\n\n | headerstyle  = background: #F0E68C\n | labelstyle   = \n | datastyle    =\n\n | header1      =[[Shahnameh]] Stories\n | label2       =\n | data2        =\n | label3       =\n | data3        =\n | label4       =\n | data4        =\n | label5       =\n | data5        =\n | label6       =\n | data6        =\n | label7       =\n | data7        =\n | header14     =\n | label15      =\n | data15       =\n | label16      =\n | data16       =\n | label17      =\n | data17       =\n | label18      =\n | data18       =\n | label19      =\n | data19       =\n | label20      =\n | data20       =\n | header21     =\n | label22      =\n | data22       =\n | label23      =\n | data23       =\n | label24      =\n | data24       =\n | label25      =\n | data25       =\n}}\n\n\n\n'''Zal and Rudaba''' ({{lang-fa|\u0632\u0627\u0644 \u0648 \u0631\u0648\u062f\u0627\u0628\u0647}}) are the fate of two lovers in Shahnameh. [[Z\u0101l]]'s love for [[Rudaba]] begins when he enters the suburbs of Kabol under the rule of the governor and hears [[Mehrab Kaboli|Mehrab]], the ruler of [[Kabul (Shahnameh)|Kabol]], have a daughter in the palace. Zal was ruling as a teenager in Zabol and was ordered by King [[Manuchehr]] of Iran. It was likely that the tax collection of the countries under the command of Iran was with Zal, and he camped with his battalion on the outskirts of Kabol<ref>Zal traveled to Hinduwan and entered the cities of [[Kabul (Shahnameh)|Kabol]], [[Dunbar (Shahnameh)|Dunbar]], [[Murg (Shahnameh)|Morg]] and [[Mai (Shahnameh)|Mai]].</ref>.\n\n==Dating Zal and Mehrab==\nMehrab was the ruler of Kabul and the father of Rudaba. Mehrab paid his taxes to [[S\u0101m]] as usual, but now his successor is Zal. Mehrab found that Zal had camped on the outskirts of the city, visiting in the morning but with an annual ransom. When Zal was aware of Mehrab's arrival, he accepted her and welcomed her into the Zuboliani tradition and placed her in a high position in parliament. When the party ended and a farewell to Mehrab, one of Zal's commanders told him that Mehrab had a beautiful daughter in the palace. And Zal fell in love with Mehrab's daughter.\n\nZal was upset at night, but the next day Mehrab went to Zal's tent again for lunch. Zal was very happy about the arrival of Mehrab. He asked Mehrab what he wanted to express, the throne, the royal seal, the sword or the crown. These compliments indicated a lover. And while he had not yet seen the [[Rudaba]]. In response, Mehrab said, \"I only have one wish to be my guest. Despite the esoteric desire, Zal said Sam would not allow me to do so, and Mehrab left hi tent discomfort.\n\n==Zal and white hair==\nMehrab returned to the palace and praised Zal's glamorous qualities for his wife [[Sindukht]], but said the gladiator had only one flaw and that he had white hair. [[Rudaba]] heard the talk but fell in love with Zal' character and wished he could understand her better. Rudaba was restless like Zal and sent five of her slaves to the Zal tent to get to know each other. Eventually, one night Zal climbed the wall of the palace with Rudaba's escort, and the two lovers' wishes came true. But an acute problem later emerged, and it was the [[Iran (Shahnameh)|Iran]] king's opposition to their marriage<ref>[[Manuchehr]] believed that their marriage would be a two-pronged generation that would be dangerous for Iran. And [[Rostam]] was the result of their marriage. </ref>. \n\n== 