s on Poetry]\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/ipa/poems/komunyakaa/biography.php Biography]\n* [http://www.poets.org/poet.php/prmPID/22 Profile and poems at Poets.org]\n* [http://www.poetry.la/page212.html Video of Yusef's reading, 3/09/09, at the Boston Court Theatre in Pasadena, CA, as featured on Poetry.LA]\n\n{{PulitzerPrize PoetryAuthors 1976\u20132000}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komunyakaa, Yusef}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Colorado State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Bogalusa, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Poets from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Poetry winners]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Colorado Springs alumni]]\n[[Category:University of New Orleans faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers of American Southern literature]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yusef_Komunyakaa"}
{"title_page": "Bye Bye Bye", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 single by *NSYNC}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{about|the song by *NSYNC|the song by Jellyfish|Spilt Milk (Jellyfish album)|the song by Cute|Bye Bye Bye!|the song by School of Seven Bells|Disconnect from Desire}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Bye Bye Bye\n| cover      = Byebyebye.jpg\n| alt        = The five band members are facing towards the center, in front of a black background. The song's title is above them.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[NSYNC]]\n| album      = [[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|No Strings Attached]]\n| B-side     = Could It Be You\n| released   = {{Start date|2000|1|11}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Cassette single|cassette]]|[[Gramophone record|7\"]]}}\n| recorded   = September 1999\n| studio     = {{ubl|Battery Studios {{small|([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])}}|[[Cheiron Studios]] {{small|([[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]])}}|Cove City Sound Studios {{small|([[Orlando]], [[Florida]])}}}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=20}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Kristian \nLundin|Jake Schulze|[[Andreas Carlsson]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Kristian Lundin|Jake Schulze}}\n| prev_title = [[Music of My Heart]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[I'll Never Stop]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|Eo-KmOd3i7s|\"Bye Bye Bye\"}} }}\n}}\n\n\"'''Bye Bye Bye'''\" is a song by the American [[boy band]] [[NSYNC]]. It was released on January 10th, 2000 as the [[lead single]] from their third studio album ''[[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|No Strings Attached]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Manning |first=Kara |title='NSYNC Lines Up Release Dates In Wake Of Settlement |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1432527/nsync-lines-up-release-dates-wake-settlement.jhtml |publisher=MTV Networks |date=January 3, 2000|accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref> The song was written and produced by [[Kristian Lundin]] and Jake Schulze, with additional writing by [[Andreas Carlsson]]. Its lyrics describe the end of a romantic relationship; it was reported to also reference the group's separation from their manager [[Lou Pearlman]] and their record label [[RCA Records]].\n\n\"Bye Bye Bye\" was a commercial success, peaking at number 4 on the US [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] and within the top 10 in almost every country in which it charted. The song received a [[2001 Grammy Awards|Grammy]] nomination in 2001 for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], but lost to [[U2]]'s \"[[Beautiful Day]]\".\n\n==Background==\n\"Bye Bye Bye\" was written and produced by [[Kristian Lundin]] and Jake Schulze, as part of [[Cheiron Studios|Cheiron Productions]], with additional writing by [[Andreas Carlsson]]. Lundin stated that it was \"totally production driven\" and \"created from the kick and the bass up\".<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Kristian_Lundin_Interview.html |title=Interview With Kristian Lundin |publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=Jan 7, 2003 |accessdate=April 10, 2011}}</ref> Carlsson wrote the song's lyrics while he was taking a driver's test in Stockholm, Sweden.<ref name=\"ET20\"/> The song was originally intended to be recorded by English boy band [[Five (band)|5ive]], but they rejected it as they wanted to become a rap band.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/exclusive-q-a-simon-cowell-on-one-directions-rise-to-stardom-20120409|title=Exclusive QA: Simon Cowell on One Direction's Rise to Stardom|author=Andy Greene|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 9, 2012|accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref> Carlsson recalled that one of the band members immediately called for security and left for the airport.<ref name=\"ET20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/nsyncs-no-strings-attached-turns-20-inside-making-the-hit-album-143277|title=*NSYNC's 'No Strings Attached' Turns 20: How Destiny's Child, Heartache & Lawsuit Fueled the Album (Exclusive)|last=Tailor|first=Leena|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The song's chorus was initially written as a rap, where 5ive assumed that they would be competing against [[Eminem]].<ref name=\"NPR\"/> Prior to its official release in 2000, the song was played at the LIFEbeat AIDS benefit concert in New York on December 1, 1999.<ref>{{cite web|title=Short 'N SYNC Set Wows Girls At Benefit|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/520369/short-n-sync-set-wows-girls-at-benefit/|accessdate=30 May 2017|work=[[MTV News]]|date=2 December 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Bye Bye Bye\" was influenced by [[Destiny's Child]]'s \"[[Bills, Bills, Bills]]\", as the producers wanted to produce a [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] sound in their production.<ref name=\"ET20\"/>  The song's composition of repeating the title at the beginning and ending of the chorus was used as a foundation for future songs, including \"[[Into You (Ariana Grande song)|Into You]]\" by [[Ariana Grande]].<ref name=\"ET20\"/>  The song begins with a string crescendo that climbs before [[Justin Timberlake]]'s nasal falsetto ad-libs \"Hey, hey\", leading to the five-part harmony of the song's title.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/20/818464377/nsync-no-strings-attached-20th-anniversary-timberlake-backstreet|title=The Future According To NSYNC: 20 Years Of 'No Strings Attached'|last=Sherman|first=Maria|website=[[NPR]]|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>  Instrumentation consisted of \"buzzy electronics\" adding texture to the band's vocals, in contrast to the [[doo-wop]] of the [[Backstreet Boys]], as well as hard drums, with a snare and kick.<ref name=\"NPR\"/> \n\nLyrically, \"Bye Bye Bye\" describes a man's desires to end a romantic relationship with a difficult significant other.  Carlsson initially wrote the song after his girlfriend left him for another man, whom she married and had children for over twenty years.<ref name=\"ET20\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Bye Bye Bye\" was met with generally favorable reviews from music critics. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] described the song as a \"piledriving dance number with the catchiest chorus they've ever sang\".<ref name=\"ErlewineAllrev\">{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |title=''No Strings Attached'' - *NSYNC|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=no-strings-attached-r468331|tab=review|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2011-08-19}}</ref> Robert Christgau commented that it featured \"prefab rhythm at its most efficient.\"<ref name=\"Christgaurev\">{{cite web |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau|title=CG: 'N Sync|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=nsync |publisher=RobertChristgau.com |accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s  Jason Lipshutz ranked it third on the list \"Top 20 Essential Boy Band Songs,\" describing the song as \"an absolute monster of a lead single.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6627352/boy-band-songs-top-20-essential |title=Top 20 Essential Boy Band Songs |last=Lipshutz |first=Jason |date=July 13, 2015 |work=Billboard |access-date=March 11, 2017}}</ref> Also for ''Billboard'', in 2018 the staff listed the single 12th on \"The 100 Greatest Boy Band Songs of All Time,\" writing, \"It's already one of the most decisive breakup anthems in pop history, with an iconic dance move to match[...] the stomping, quintessential Max Martin beat and echoing hook helped ''No Strings Attached'' go platinum in one day.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=April 23, 2018 |title=The 100 Greatest Boy Band Songs of All Time: Critics' Picks |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8362499/greatest-boy-band-songs-of-all-time-top-100 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' staff ranked it as the sixth-greatest boy band song of all time, writing, \"it remains their defining track, a four-minute blast of big hooks, tight harmonies and intriguingly meta subtext.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-greatest-boy-band-songs-of-all-time-20150924/kat-tun-real-face-2006-20150923 |title=50 Greatest Boy Band Songs of All Time |last=Walters |first=Barry |last2=Stevens |first2=Kat |last3=Spanos |first3=Brittany  |last4=Murray |first4=Nick |last5=Benjamin |first5=Jeff |last6=Johnston |first6=Maura |date=September 24, 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=March 10, 2018}}</ref> However, another editor from the same magazine listed it as the 17th most annoying song of all time in 2007.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140331080835/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/blogs/staff-blog/the-20-most-annoying-songs-20070702 The 20 Most Annoying Songs | 2007 | Rolling Stone<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2013, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''{{'}}s Kathy Iandoli ranked it as the best boy band song ever.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/10/best-boy-band-songs/ |title=The 30 Best Boy Band Songs |last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |date=October 2, 2013 |work=Complex |access-date=March 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe song won \"Best Pop Video\", \"Best Choreography in a Video\", and \"Viewer's Choice\" at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]], the most awarded to a single video that year. It also won a Radio Music Radio award in 2000 for best song of the year. The song was nominated for \"Record of the Year\" and \"Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal\" at the [[2001 Grammy Awards]]. Other awards included 3 Teen Choice Awards in 2000 (Choice Single, Choice Music Video, and Song of the Summer),  MuchMusic Video Music Award (Favorite International Group for \"Bye Bye Bye\") and Blockbuster Entertainment Award 2001 (category Favorite Single for \"Bye Bye Bye\").\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Bye Bye Bye\" debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at #42, the week of January 29, 2000, reaching the Top 10 by the week of March 4. The song remained in the Top 10 through May 20, 2000, for 12 weeks. The single peaked at #4 in April 2000 for two consecutive weeks. On the [[Mainstream Top 40]] chart the song reached number one on March 4, 2000 and stayed at the top of the chart for ten weeks,  making it one of the songs with most weeks at number one on that chart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7603787/the-chainsmokers-closer-pop-songs-chart-no-1-run|title=The Chainsmokers' 'Closer' Ties for Second-Longest No. 1 Run Atop Pop Songs Chart|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref> The song was the most added pop single to radio of all time, being added to over 200 radio stations in the first week alone. The record was previously held by rivals the [[Backstreet Boys]].<ref>[http://www.allbusiness.com/retail/retailers-electronics-appliance-retailing-radio/6088401-1.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207220049/http://www.allbusiness.com/retail/retailers-electronics-appliance-retailing-radio/6088401-1.html|date=February 7, 2009}}</ref> The song was a bigger hit internationally, reaching the top of the charts in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] and number 3 in the [[United Kingdom]]. On the week of March 24, 2014, the song re-entered the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]] at number 14.<ref>[http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2464]</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\nThe video was directed by [[Wayne Isham]], and was released on January 11, 2000. The budget was estimated to be $1 million, which was attributed to the band wanting to be noticed on [[MTV]]. The song's dance routine was  choreographed by [[Darrin Henson]], who received a phone call from NSYNC's manager [[Johnny Wright (music manager)|Johnny Wright]], as he was about to quit the music industry after missing out on a [[MTV Video Music Award|VMA]] for [[Jordan Knight]]'s \"[[Give It to You (Jordan Knight song)|Give It to You]]\". Henson flew to [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] in 1999, where the band were performing at the [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], so that he would be able to listen to the track. The band rehearsed at the Alley Kat Studio in Los Angeles over a few days, where Henson stated that he implemented moves which cannot be replicated by other groups.<ref name=\"EW20\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/2020/01/11/making-of-nsync-bye-bye-bye-music-video/|title=Inside the making of NSYNC's iconic 'Bye Bye Bye' music video|last=Kinane|first=Ruth|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 11, 2020|access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> In a 2020 interview with ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Henson discussed how he formulated the dance:<ref name=\"EW20\"/><blockquote>I turned the music up as loud as it could go [...] I came up with the pumping hand \u2014 that\u2019s the [[Raised fist|black power fist]] \u2014 and the hand going across the front during the 'bye bye bye' lyric is the 'stop talking s\u2014.' I come from the Bronx, and in New York whenever somebody said something, you'd put your hand up in a talking manner, like open and close, meaning, 'stop talking s\u2014.'</blockquote>\n\n[[File:Fillmore, CA, View W, Old Telegraph Road, October 13, 2011 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|Parts of the video were filmed in [[Fillmore, California]], as it was the only place for the train scene to be filmed.]] \n\nThey contacted Isham through the phone, before he met them during dance rehearsals for the song.<ref name=\"Billboard20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9344530/nsync-video-director-wayne-isham-interview|title='F--k, Let's Just Go For It': *NSYNC Video Director Wayne Isham Talks 'Bye Bye Bye' & 'It's Gonna Be Me' Clips|last=Daw|first=Robbie|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> During the music video's shoot, the band were fastened to bungee cords, mimicking [[puppet]]s on strings, as well as performing their choreography in a blue [[gimbal]] room, which Isham pointed out that it was inspired by [[Gene Kelly]] during the 1940s, as well as [[Lionel Richie]]'s video for \"[[Dancing on the Ceiling]]\", which was directed and choreographed by [[Stanley Donen]].<ref name=\"EW20\"/><ref name=\"Billboard20\"/> During the speeding train sequence, [[Joey Fatone]] and [[Chris Kirkpatrick]]  performed their own stunts as they jumped from one train carriage to another, as a [[Steadicam]] operator needed to be replaced mid-scene, due to being uncomfortable with the risk. [[JC Chasez]] and [[Lance Bass]] were placed in a red [[Dodge Viper|Dodge Viper RT/10]] as part of a car-chase scene inspired by Chasez's favorite film, ''[[Ronin (film)|Ronin]]'', where the film's stunt coordinators were hired to assist the shoot. The scene where Bass and Chasez drop into the car was filmed with a [[Semi-trailer truck|18 wheeler]] carrying a pole, which allowed the two to drop into the car.<ref name=\"EW20\"/> Both scenes were shot in [[Fillmore, California]], as it was the only place to film the train sequence.<ref name=\"Billboard20\"/> In an episode of ''[[Making the Video]]'', [[Justin Timberlake]] explained his reaction to shooting his scene in the music video:<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite episode|title=*NSYNC: Bye Bye Bye|series=[[Making the Video]]|network=[[MTV]]|date=January 23, 2000|season=2|number=2|language=en}}</ref><blockquote>JC and Lance jumped into a moving automobile, Chris and Joey are on top of a train running, so I think I got off easiest on the stunts [...] All I have to do is run, but I have to make it look good \u2014 I can't look like a dork when I'm running. Gotta be cool.</blockquote>\n\nHenson eventually won an [[MTV Video Music Award]] [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|for Best Choreography]] at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]], while NSYNC also won [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Pop Video|Best Pop Video]] at the same ceremony.<ref name=\"EW20\"/>\n\n===Synopsis===\n[[File:Bye Bye Bye music video.png|thumb|right|The members of the group portray [[puppet]]s, in reference to their destiny being controlled by [[Lou Pearlman]] during their legal dispute.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baker|first=Soren|title=Flashback 2000: 'N Sync, Britney, Eminem, and Backstreet Boys Set Sales Records|url=http://music.yahoo.com/library/default.asp?m=content&add=news&i=12042460&|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=December 31, 2000|access-date=August 20, 2011}}</ref>]]\nThe video begins with NSYNC being manipulated as puppets by an evil puppet master, portrayed by [[Kim Smith (model)|Kim Smith]]. She cuts Joey Fatone and Chris Kirkpatrick loose first, as they run over the top of a speeding train and hide among the passengers to escape. She then cuts Justin Timberlake loose next, which he outruns her trained dogs inside a warehouse, eventually escaping into the pouring rain.\n\nLance Bass and JC Chasez are finally cut loose, as they fall into a red Dodge Viper RT/10. They speed away from her, as she drives a silver [[BMW Z3 (E36/4)|BMW Z3]]. Eventually, they make a sudden u-turn when they are blocked by a truck, while the puppet master is forced to brake slower, allowing them to escape.\n\nAll the scenes are interspersed with shots of the band dancing in a rotating blue gimbal with a fixed camera, making them appear as though they are on different planes of gravity. The video edit of the song also briefly pauses the music when Justin lands in the warehouse, as well as when Lance and JC land on the car and insert a [[cassette tape]] into the car, and their u-turn at the end of the video. The chorus is also extended twice at the end of the video; the first showcasing the band inside the box, while the second shows scenes of Lance and JC speeding away from the puppet master.\n\n===Reception===\nThe video reached #1 on ''[[Total Request Live|TRL]]'' for 25 straight days, second only to \"[[U Drive Me Crazy]]\", which made it to 26 straight days at #1.<ref>[http://atrl.net/trlarchive/?s=numberones ATRL - The TRL Archive - Number Ones<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The video placed at #60 on [[MuchMusic]]'s 100 Best Videos. The video debuted on ''TRL'' January 24, 2000. In 2018, [[iHeartRadio]]'s Nicole Mastrogiannis ranked Timberlake's appearance in the video as the top \"Iconic Music Moments From the 00s.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2018-04-27-25-iconic-music-moments-from-the-00s-youll-never-forget/ |title=25 Iconic Music Moments From the 00s You'll Never Forget |last=Mastrogiannis |first=Nicole |date=April 25, 2018 |work=iHeartRadio |access-date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> The same year ''Billboard'' critics ranked it 21st among the \"greatest music videos of the 21st century.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8466543/100-greatest-music-videos-of-the-21st-century |title=The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 21st Century: Critics' Picks |date=July 24, 2018 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, the music video has over 209 million views on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eo-KmOd3i7s|title=*NSYNC - Bye Bye Bye|date=October 25, 2009|publisher=*NSYNC|via=[[YouTube]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable unsortable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Result\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2000/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325215241/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2000/|title=MTV Video Music Awards 2000: Winners|publisher=[[MTV]]|archivedate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Group Video|Best Group Video]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Pop Video|Best Pop Video]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Dance Video|Best Dance Video]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] \n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Viewer's Choice|Viewers Choice]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[MuchMusic Video Awards|2000 MuchMusic Video Awards]]\n|-\n|[[People's Choice: Favourite International Group (MMVA Award)|People's Choice: Favorite International Group]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[2001 Grammy Awards]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/nsync |title=*NSYNC |work=Grammy.com |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[2001 Kids' Choice Awards]]\n|-\n|Favorite Song\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Teen Choice Awards|2000 Teen Choice Awards]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1122852/nsync-dominate-teen-choice-awards/ |title=*NSync Dominate Teen Choice Awards - MTV |date=August 7, 2000 |work=MTV |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|Choice Single\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''CD single'''\n# \"Bye Bye Bye\" \u2013 3:19\n# \"Bye Bye Bye\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:19\n# \"Could It Be You\" \u2013 3:41\n{{col-2}}\n'''Remixes'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/NSYNC-Bye-Bye-Bye/release/1146460|title=*NSYNC - Bye Bye Bye (CD)|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref>\n#\"Bye Bye Bye\" (Teddy Riley's Funk Remix) \u2013 4:50\n#\"Bye Bye Bye\" (Teddy Riley's Club Remix) \u2013 5:28\n#\"Bye Bye Bye\" (Riprock 'n' Alex G. Club Remix) \u2013 6:32 \t\n#\"Bye Bye Bye\" (Riprock 'n' Alex G. Club Remix Radio Edit) \u2013 4:53 \t\n#\"Bye Bye Bye\" (Sal Dano's Peak Hour Dub) \u2013 8:30\n{{col-end}}\n==Credits and personnel==\n;Recording<ref name=\"bye\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Bye Bye Bye |others=[[NSYNC]] |date=2000 |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Jive Records]] |id=9250202}}</ref>\n*Recorded at Battery Studios, NYC; Cove City Sound Studios, Orlando, FL; and [[Cheiron Studios]], Stockholm, Sweden.\n\n;Personnel<ref name=\"bye\"/>\n*[[Kristian Lundin]] \u2013 songwriter, producer\n*Jake Schulze \u2013 songwriter, producer\n*[[Andreas Carlsson]] \u2013 songwriter\n*Michael Tucker \u2013 recording engineer/[[Roland TR-909]]\n*Bray Merritt \u2013 assistant engineer\n*Casey LaPoint - harp\n*Esbj\u00f6rn \u00d6hrwall \u2013 guitar\n*Tom Coyne \u2013 mastering\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2000)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|1|artist=*N Sync|song=Bye Bye Bye|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|12|artist=*N Sync|song=Bye Bye Bye|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|7|artist=*N Sync|song=Bye Bye Bye|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|21|artist=*N Sync|song=Bye Bye Bye|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|1|chartid=9761|accessdate=November 14, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadaadultcontemporary|16|chartid=7232|accessdate=November 14, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadadance|25|chartid=7227|accessdate=November 14, 2018}}\n|-\n|Europe ([[European Hot 100]])<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?lr=&rview=1&id=0A4EAAAAMBAJ&q=n+sync#v=snippet&q=n%20sync&f=false Billboard - Google Books]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n{{singlechart|Finland|7|artist=*N Sync|song=Bye Bye Bye|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|46|artist=*N Sync|song=Bye Bye Bye|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|4|songid=4176|artist=*N Syn